Implement opaque annotation checking in tap transform

DESCRIPTION:
The tap transform (koru_std/taps.kz) must respect [opaque] annotations
on events to prevent infinite recursion and allow internal implementation
events to be called safely from tap handlers.

ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA:
1. Tap transform walks program's event declarations during processing
2. Collects events marked with [opaque] annotation
3. When matching invocations for wrapping, skips any event that has [opaque]
4. Test passes: "Hello\n[INTERNAL] input:hello\n"

BLOCKS:
- tests/regression/300_ADVANCED_FEATURES/310_COMPTIME/310_018_ccp_opt_in
- tests/regression/300_ADVANCED_FEATURES/310_COMPTIME/310_019_ccp_flag_injection

RATIONALE:
Without opaque support, universal taps recursively tap themselves through
internal events, causing infinite loops and type checking failures.
This is critical for CCP (Compiler Control Protocol) and any other
observability systems that generate their own events.
